d with major works by Braque, Picasso, and Klee—Zeidler retrieves the theoretical resources that Einstein brought to bear on their art. Form as Revolt shows us that to rediscover Einstein's art criticism is to see the work of great modernist artists anew through the eyes of one of the most gifted left-wing formalists of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aArt historianszGermanyy20th century. 0aArt, Moderny20th centuryxHistory. 4aArt History. 4aJewish Studies.  aCarl Einstein, Einstein’s writings, Einstein's intellectual career, intellectual biography, history of modern art, modernist artists, Georges Braque, Pablo Picasso, Paul Klee, criticism of early twentieth-century art.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2016z9783110485165oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170190040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701900/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DPKb2016